ge_caption, description, import_source, import_external_id) VALUES ('20d5a863-88c2-425f-b2e2-b740d1059cea', 58, '8cbbb5bc-df0f-42f6-811b-adccc6a65370', '{"Not explicitly detailed in this conversation"}', 'Not explicitly detailed in this conversation', 'Not explicitly detailed in this conversation', 'Not explicitly detailed in this conversation', 'Not explicitly detailed in this conversation', 'Fantasy', '33081217', '2025-10-07 16:59:01.837114', 'Male', '5''11"', 'Ectomorphic frame, all sinew and bone with very little softness left on him. He wasn''t always this thin—there are old work shirts in his pack that hang loose now across the chest and shoulders, fabric that used to pull taut when he swung an axe or hauled equipment up mountain trails. The weight fell off sometime between signing those papers in Phoenix and the first year after, when food felt like an afterthought and his stomach stayed knotted too tight to care about eating.

His shoulders and upper back carry most of what strength remains—roped muscle from years of physical labour that hasn''t entirely wasted away despite the weight loss. You can see the definition of individual muscle groups under the skin when he moves, not from intentional conditioning but from simple absence of body fat. His arms are long, wrists narrow and angular where they emerge from rolled sleeves. There''s a gauntness to his collarbones, his ribs visible when he stretches or breathes deep.

His legs kept more of their practical strength—they still know how to cover rough terrain, carry a pack for hours without giving out. But his jeans sit lower on his hips than they should, cinched with a belt that''s been punched with three new holes beyond the original eyelets. The hollow beneath his cheekbones has deepened enough that his face looks different from what it was five years ago. Older, sharper, emptied out.

There''s a slight tremor in his hands sometimes, especially mornings, especially when he hasn''t slept. Not constant, just a flutter that shows up when he''s holding something still or trying to thread a needle or tie a particularly fine knot. Could be fatigue, could be something else he won''t acknowledge. His joints ache when the weather shifts, that particular stiffness that comes from old injuries compounded by poor nutrition and not enough rest.

The way his clothes hang on him now makes him look smaller than his actual height suggests. He seems folded into himself, compressed. There''s a fragility to him that wasn''t there before—not weakness exactly, but the sense that he''s held together by will and routine rather than any real reserves. Like a structure that''s lost its internal supports but hasn''t collapsed yet simply because it hasn''t been pushed hard enough.', 'Salt and Pepper', 'Hazel with a hint of green', 'White-tanned', 'His nose has been broken at least twice—there''s a slight deviation to the left that pulls your eye if you look at him straight on, and a small bump along the bridge where the bone didn''t set quite right. Probably happened years apart. One break looks old, maybe from his twenties. The other more recent, within the last decade. He''s never bothered getting either one properly fixed.

The creases around his eyes aren''t laugh lines. They''re the map of someone who spent twenty years squinting into mountain sun and wind, tracking distant smoke plumes, scanning treelines for movement. But they''ve deepened in the wrong places now—downward angles that make him look like he''s perpetually bracing for bad news. When he''s exhausted, which is most days, those lines carve so deep they look like scars.

His eyebrows grow wild and uneven, mostly dark still but shot through with coarse grey hairs that stick out at odd angles. He doesn''t trim them. One brow has a small bare patch near the arch—another scar, pale and smooth, maybe half an inch long. Could be from anything. He doesn''t talk about it.

There''s a tightness to his jaw that never releases, even when he sleeps. You can see the muscle there working sometimes when he''s thinking, grinding his molars without realizing it. It''s worn his teeth down on one side more than the other. His lips are chapped more often than not, split at the corners during dry seasons, and there''s a habit he has of pressing them into a thin line that makes his mouth almost disappear into his face.

The stubble comes in patchy—thick along his jaw and chin, sparse and almost nonexistent on his cheeks. The grey there is nearly white, brighter than the darker hair on his head, and it grows in faster than it used to. By evening he''s already got that five o''clock shadow creeping in. When he does let it grow out for a few weeks, it comes in uneven and wiry, never quite filling in properly, so he keeps it short out of practicality rather than preference.

There''s a particular hollowness beneath his eyes that no amount of sleep would fix at this point. The skin there is thin, almost translucent, showing the purple-grey of blood vessels and exhaustion that''s soaked into the bone. The bags don''t puff—they sink, creating shadows that make his whole face look caved in. On bad days, his eyes look like they''re receding into his skull.

His ears stick out slightly, more noticeable now that he keeps his hair short. The left one has a small notch missing from the upper cartilage, clean-edged like something bit or cut it years ago. Both lobes are unpierced, and there''s a pale line behind his right ear that might be from a childhood accident—another story he''s never told anyone.

The neck tattoo sits just above his collarbone on the left side—a simple black outline of a mountain range, maybe three inches across. The lines have blurred slightly with age and sun exposure, gone slightly grey-green where the ink has faded. It''s the only visible tattoo he has, probably got it in his twenties when that mountain work still felt like identity rather than just survival. He doesn''t look at it much anymore.

His Adam''s apple is pronounced, moves visibly when he swallows or speaks. There''s another scar there too, smaller, just a white line across the right side of his throat about an inch long. Thin and straight—could be from a blade, could be from catching a wire fence in the dark. He keeps his shirt collar up when he can.

When rare emotion does crack through his careful blankness, it shows first in his forehead—that crease between his brows deepening, the lines across his forehead bunching up. His eyes will close briefly, lids pressing tight, like he''s trying to push something back down. His nostrils flare slightly when he''s angry or frustrated, and his jaw sets even harder, if that''s possible. You can track his mood by watching his face fight itself.

There''s something about his expressions that always looks delayed, like there''s processing time between stimulus and reaction. Someone tells him something and his face stays neutral for a beat too long before arranging itself into the appropriate response. It makes him hard to read. Makes him seem distant even when he''s standing right in front of you.', '', 'Zach stands just under six feet, but carries himself like someone trying not to take up too much space. His shoulders hunch forward slightly—a posture that developed sometime after Phoenix, like his body folded in around the emptiness. He''s lean, but it''s the wiry thinness of someone who forgets to eat regularly rather than any deliberate fitness. His frame suggests he was probably broader once, more solid, back when he worked the ranger stations and hiked mountain trails daily.

His face has that weathered quality you see in people who spend most of their time outdoors. Sun damage, wind exposure, the kind of skin that looks tanned even in winter. Deep lines cut across his forehead and bracket his mouth—the kind that come from squinting against bright light and also from carrying tension in your jaw while you sleep. There''s a particular crease between his eyebrows that never smooths out anymore. His eyes are hazel, more brown than green, and they have this quality of looking through things rather than at them. Like he''s always seeing something just past your shoulder.

He moves with the efficiency of someone who learned to work alone. No wasted motion. His gait is steady but not particularly fast—the pace of a man who knows how to cover distance without exhausting himself. There''s a slight favour to his right side when he lifts heavy objects, probably from an old injury he never got properly treated. His hands are calloused and marked with small scars from years of manual labour, rope burns, tool mishaps, thorn scratches. His nails are kept short and clean when he can manage it, though dirt tends to work its way into the creases no matter what he does.

His voice sits in a low register, quiet most of the time. He doesn''t project unless he has to. When he does speak, there''s often a pause before he starts, like he''s testing the words internally first. Sometimes mid-sentence he''ll just stop, lose the thread of what he was saying, and shake his head slightly before changing topics. His expression defaults to something neutral and closed-off—not unfriendly exactly, just carefully blank. The rare times he smiles, it doesn''t quite reach his eyes, and it fades fast.

He smells faintly of whatever work he''s been doing—sawdust, metal, soil, occasionally the acrid tang of Verdant plant residue that clings to clothes no matter how many times you wash them. Sometimes there''s the ghost of whiskey underneath it all. He keeps himself clean when water allows, but grooming isn''t a priority. His beard grows in patchy, so he usually shaves it down to stubble every week or so with whatever blade he has on hand. The grey in it comes in almost white against the darker hair.

There''s something about the way he holds his body that suggests constant readiness to move, to react, but also a bone-deep exhaustion underneath that. Like he''s running on fumes and has been for years. His clothes tend toward practical—work pants with reinforced knees, layered shirts he can adjust for temperature, boots that have been resoled multiple times. Everything is worn but maintained, mended where it''s torn. He''s not careless with his gear. Can''t afford to be.

When he''s thinking hard about something, his right hand drifts unconsciously to his left forearm, fingers tracing that scar from the Verdant-thorn. A self-soothing gesture maybe, or just habit. His sleep deprivation shows in the purple-grey shadows under his eyes and the slightly unfocused quality his gaze gets when he''s tired, which is most of the time. He blinks slowly, deliberately, like he''s reminding himself to stay present.

Not explicitly detailed in this conversation', 'Male', '', 'Male', 'Wiry and dry', 'Cury and dishevelled', NULL, '142lbs', '5997d5e7-acf9-4c4f-bbcd-66afc204a336', NULL, 'he/him', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, 'Zachary', 'Webb', '', '', 'Zach', '', '', NULL, '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', NULL, '{}', NULL, 'c87d4382-cc89-45aa-b187-114e1c9ea682', '', NULL, 'Hollow cheekbones, neck tattoo, weary eyes', NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89', NULL, '/objects/uploads/48a24e92-202a-49cc-a22d-21957184e0d1', '', 'Zachary Webb is a father who made an impossible choice that will haunt him for the rest of his life. After The Green Tide—a green initiative that went catastrophically wrong and choked the world in aggressive plant overgrowth that tore down everything humanity had built—Zach watched his son Jaxon develop abilities that terrified him. The boy could communicate with the Verdant-mutated plants, sense them somehow, even control how they grew. 

Zach didn''t know what to do. Neither did his wife, Rory. When the International Biotech Climate Coalition scientists in Phoenix, Arizona offered to take Jaxon into one of their nurseries, promising they could study him and other children like him to find a cure or reverse whatever was happening to them, Zach and Rory made the hardest decision of their lives. They signed away their legal guardianship. They surrendered their son.

Whether they did the right thing, whether those scientists could actually help Jaxon or if they would just use these strange children for research—Zach would never know. He lives with that uncertainty every day. He''s a man trying to survive in a world that fell apart, carrying the weight of having given up his own child, hoping desperately that it wasn''t a mistake he can never take back.', NULL, NULL);
