ge_caption, description, import_source, import_external_id) VALUES ('1ce382ef-c04e-4737-80a3-d9055cba715f', 49, 'bcbc4563-bb66-43f7-995c-297ed3ec1d6a', NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Fantasy', '33081217', '2025-10-07 16:59:00.279771', 'Female', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '5997d5e7-acf9-4c4f-bbcd-66afc204a336', NULL, 'she/her', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, 'Sylvia', 'Langford', 'Emily', '', '', 'Dr.', '', NULL, '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', NULL, '{}', NULL, 'She drinks her coffee black now, not because she likes it but because rationing makes powdered creamer a luxury she won''t justify. Small sacrifices add up.

The other researchers have learned not to interrupt her before noon. Mornings are for the dangerous work—the live samples, the specimens that still pulse with that sickly bioluminescence. Her hands don''t shake anymore when she handles them. They did once—everyone''s did. But fear becomes mundane when you face it every single day for years on end.

She''s developed a reputation for being cold. Uncompromising. Someone started a rumour that she cares more about her research than her own sons, which isn''t fair but also isn''t entirely wrong. How do you explain that saving humanity requires a certain detachment? That if she let herself feel the full weight of every loss, every failed trial, every settlement that went dark on the communications network—she''d never get out of bed.

Silvan asked her once why she couldn''t just accept things the way they are now. He was thirteen. Already growing up in a world where the Verdancy was normal, where humanity living underground felt like the natural order. The question haunted her for weeks. Still does, if she''s being honest.

She has a tell when she''s close to a breakthrough—starts humming under her breath, old songs from before. Classic rock her father used to play. Milan noticed it years ago. The rest of the team has caught on. When Dr. Langford starts humming "Landslide" while pipetting samples, everyone gets a little more hopeful. A little more tense.

Her handwriting has gotten worse. Chicken scratch that only her lab assistant can reliably decode. Too many hours gripping instruments, peering through microscopes. The optometrist keeps suggesting she needs reading glasses. She keeps forgetting to get them, or maybe it''s not forgetting. Maybe it''s the same reason she doesn''t schedule the dental work or address the persistent ache in her lower back. Maintenance feels frivolous when the world''s ending in slow motion.

She lies to Milan sometimes about when she last ate. It''s easier than the lecture, the worried crease between his eyebrows. He''s got enough to worry about.', '', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89', NULL, '/objects/uploads/c2541f05-992a-42f2-9edd-f4f3aab7436a', '', 'Dr. Sylvia Langford carries the weight of a world that tried to save itself and failed spectacularly. There''s something in the way she holds herself—shoulders perpetually tight, like she''s bracing for the next crisis—that speaks to years of watching green tendrils dismantle civilization one city block at a time.

Her hands tell their own story. Chemical burns have left faint marks across her knuckles, souvenirs from countless failed experiments in the early days when desperation made everyone a little reckless with safety protocols. She still works with an intensity that unsettles some of her colleagues, hunched over microscopes and sample trays for twelve, fourteen, sometimes sixteen hours at a stretch. Sleep has become negotiable.

The salt flats changed her. There''s a particular kind of paranoia you develop when you''ve lived as a refugee, when you''ve seen what happens to settlements that get complacent. She keeps emergency supplies stashed in odd corners of the bunker—water purification tablets taped under her desk, a go-bag hidden behind filing cabinets. Old habits. Her boys used to tease her about it, back when they were younger and thought their mother was being overcautious.

She remembers the Mojave nights in Espera with an almost painful clarity. The way the sky stretched endlessly dark and clean, no verdant canopy choking out the stars. How quiet it could be. The bunker''s different—constant hum of ventilation systems, the sterile smell of recycled air. Sometimes she misses the salt and dust, even knowing what they''d fled from.

Her marriage to Milan has weathered more than most. They don''t always agree on her methods, her refusal to consider that maybe the Verdancy can''t be reversed. Maybe shouldn''t be. But he understands the drive, even when it scares him. Even when she forgets to come to bed.

There''s a photograph she keeps in her lab coat pocket, creased from handling. Her family in Espera, before the Archive recruitment. Everyone''s squinting against the desert sun, Milan''s arm around her waist, the twins making faces at the camera.', NULL, NULL);
