INSERT INTO public.guides (id, title, description, content, excerpt, category, read_time, difficulty, rating, author, tags, published, created_at, updated_at, folder_id, user_id, category_id) VALUES ('3b20771a-480c-454c-a3aa-f7c97509c6a5', 'What is Worldbuilding?', 'Learn about what world building is, how it works, and how to get started your own world building adventure!', '<p style="text-align: left;">World-building is the process of creating and building an imaginary world that is often associated with a fictional universe. It''s all about creating a rich and consistent setting that feels real to your audience.<br></p><p>The elements of a fictional world are like the building blocks of a new reality that we are trying to create. We can break them down into two main categories: the physical world itself and its inhabitants.<br></p><p>Your world consists of two fundamental elements: the physical realm and its inhabitants. The physical realm encompasses the natural environment—geography, climate, and the laws of physics that govern reality. The inhabitants breathe life into this space: people, creatures, races, societies, languages, histories, and the organizations they build.</p><h3>Physical World-Building</h3><p>The foundation of your world is its physical form. This includes everything from the stars in the sky to the minerals found in the ground.<br></p><p>A few key questions we can ask ourselves to start creating our physical world are things like:</p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p><strong>Astronomy &amp; Cosmology: </strong>What does the sky look like? Does our world have multiple suns or moons? This will also typically affect phenomena such as our world''s seasons, tides, and calendars.</p></li><li><p><strong>Geography &amp; Geology</strong>: What is the shape of the land? Are there supercontinents, vast oceans, river deltas or towering mountain ranges? This will shape our world''s borders, trade routes, and where people live.</p></li><li><p><strong>Flora &amp; Fauna:</strong> What kinds of plants and animals exist in our world? Are they familiar, or completely fantastical? This will help us determine our world''s food sources, resources, and potential dangers for its inhabitants<br></p></li></ul><img class="editor-image rounded-lg" src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/2150/sky-space-dark-galaxy.jpg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;h=650&amp;w=940" width="476" data-align="right" style="width: 476px; float: right; margin: 0px 0px 1rem 1.5rem;"><h3 style="text-align: left;">Astronomy &amp; Cosmology</h3><p>Let''s think about the sky of our fictional world, because the choices you make here will ripple through everything else. The colour of the sky, how fast your planet spins, the angle of its tilt—these aren''t just aesthetic decisions. They fundamentally reshape how your world works and its laws of nature. Say you decide that your world orbits a red dwarf instead of a sun like ours. Suddenly, your days feel drastically different. The light will have this rust-coloured quality that bleeds across everything, making shadows deeper and colours richer. Your characters experience sunrises and sunsets that aren''t the familiar oranges and pinks that we know—they''re alien, unsettling, and beautiful in a way that makes readers feel they''re somewhere otherworldly. This would also affect that planet’s rotation speed. A planet that spins twice as fast as Earth? Well, your days would shorter, which means its seasons compress. Autumn might arrive and leave just as quickly in what feels like a few weeks. The agricultural cycles break and maybe the culture that develops there might be obsessed with rapid change, adaptation, and urgency. Compare that image to a sluggish world that turns once every forty hours. It feels lazy and languid, with dawn that feels like it takes forever to arrive each day. The planet’s tilt is your also your seasonal switch. Earth tilts at 23.5 degrees, giving us dramatic seasonal swings. Tilt it more, and you get wild extremes—punishing winters or scorching summers with nothing in between. Tilt it less, and seasons fade into irrelevance. Some regions might barely notice they are changing at all. These choices aren''t background details, they''re the bones of your world. To get started with developing your world’s astronomy and cosmology, you can ask yourself questions like:</p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>What is the main star of this world like? Is it a single, sun-like star? A giant red star? A binary system with two stars? The type of star our world revolves around will determine the heat and light that our world gets, and can even affect its atmosphere.</p></li></ul><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>What is this planet''s orbit like? Does it have a circular orbit that gives us stable, predictable seasons? Or does it have a more eccentric orbit that creates extreme temperature fluctuations and seasonal swings?</p></li><li><p>Does the planet have any moons? How many moons does it have and how big are they? This will influence any tides the world has, how much nighttime light is available to its inhabitants, and can even influence your world''s mythology.<br></p></li></ul><img class="editor-image rounded-lg" src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/288093/pexels-photo-288093.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;h=650&amp;w=940" data-align="left" style="float: left; margin: 0px 1.5rem 1rem 0px;"><h3>Geography &amp; Geology</h3><p>This is where we shape the actual stage for our world. Everything from the jagged coastlines and sprawling continents down to where a single mountain range cuts through a valley—each decision can have a massive impact. A river''s placement isn''t just scenery; it''s a lifeline that will determine whether a settlement in the area thrives or withers. Mountains become barriers, trade routes, and refuges. Deserts force people to cluster around oases or abandon entire regions altogether. If your continent is shaped like a horseshoe with deep bays, you get seafaring cultures and naval conflicts. Put all your mountains on one side? You''ve created a natural divide where one half stays isolated and develops differently, might speak different languages and build different traditions. Resources tend to pool where geography allows them to. Your people will follow the fertile soil, the accessible ores, and the fish-rich waters. They''ll avoid the poisoned swamps and barren highlands unless desperation or ambition drives them there. Even small decisions ripple outward where a river that runs north-south instead of east-west might completely reshape how trade flows in certain regions, which cities rise to prominence, and which ones stay small and forgotten. The distance between two regions isn''t just distance either; it''s whether those people ever truly know each other or spend centuries as distant strangers. Coastlines determine who becomes sailors, explorers, and conquerors. Landlocked areas breed different ambitions entirely. Geography isn''t just a backdrop that sets the scene for your story; it''s the invisible hand shaping everything your world becomes. To get started with developing the geography and geology of your world, you can ask yourself questions like:<br></p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>What do the continents and oceans look like? Are there massive mountain ranges, vast deserts, or sprawling archipelagos? This will shape your world''s borders, cultures, and trade.</p></li><li><p>How does the geography create different climates? A mountain range can block rain, creating a lush forest on one side and a dry desert on the other.</p></li><li><p>Where are the most important natural resources located? Things like fertile soil for farming, metal ores for building, or sources of energy will create centres of power and conflict among your world''s inhabitants.<br></p></li></ul><img class="editor-image rounded-lg" src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/34350925/pexels-photo-34350925.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;h=650&amp;w=940" data-align="right" style="float: right; margin: 0px 0px 1rem 1.5rem;"><h3>Flora &amp; Fauna</h3><p>Flora and fauna are the lifeforms that will populate our world. Designing them is your chance to make your world feel truly unique and alive by creating interesting plants and animals. <br><br>The plants and animals in your world serve several key functions in any story. You can ask yourself questions like:</p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>What provides food, medicine, clothing, and building materials for your world''s inhabitants? A rare plant might be the only cure for a plague, which drives your main plot line. These [[Natural Resources]] are essential to the world''s inhabitants for survival, power, and wealth.</p></li></ul><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>What creatures or monsters might your world''s inhabitants have to fight and what environmental hazards would they pose that people would need to overcome? A forest full of venomous insects could be a major obstacle for any hero. These dangers can create conflicts, pose risks, and be pivotal in driving specific areas of your story''s plot lines.</p></li></ul><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>What flora and fauna can be domesticated or cultivated into pets, livestock, or agricultural resources? Are any plants or animals used as symbols on a kingdom''s banner, or worshipped as gods in your world? These create core foundations for the values of [[Settlements]], create unique [[Culture]] variations within your world, and can even influence [[Religion]], [[Trade]], and more.</p></li></ul><p>There are two main approaches to creating new lifeforms for world builders:<br></p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p><strong>Twist the Familiar:</strong> We can start with a real-world animal or plant and change one key aspect of it. For example, you might have wolves with six legs, horses that can camouflage themselves, or trees that have metallic bark. This method is quick and effective for world building.</p></li><li><p>- <strong>Build from Scratch:</strong> Or, we could invent a creature from scratch, based on the unique environmental pressures of the world you have created. For example, on a planet with extremely high gravity, animals might evolve to be low to the ground and develop many legs, like armoured centipedes. This method creates truly alien, fantastical, and memorable life-forms.</p></li></ul><p>&lt;&lt; Link to Creature Generator and Plant Generator&gt;&gt;</p><img class="editor-image rounded-lg" src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/236171/pexels-photo-236171.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;h=650&amp;w=940" data-align="center" style="display: block; margin: 1rem auto;"><h2>Culture World-Building</h2><p>Culture building encompasses all of the elements that are related to a world''s sentient inhabitants, such as how the society organizes itself, who holds power and how they use it, how inhabitants communicate and express themselves creatively, what they believe in and value, and what their collective past and customs shape their present. While physical world-building creates the stag of our world, culture building creates the characters of our stories and explains how they live within our world.<br></p><p>The key to starting with culture building is to focus on the foundational elements that shape everything else in our world. The most foundational elements to culture are: survival, organization, and worldview.</p><p>When we think about fundamental components of a culture, we need to understand our inhabitants'' relationship to their environment. We can ask ourselves questions like:<br></p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>How does the society gets its food, water, and shelter? Are they settled farmers in a fertile valley, nomadic herders on a vast steppe, or seafaring traders on a coastal archipelago? The environment and survival methods of these settlements will dictate their daily lives, their skills, and their most essential needs.</p></li><li><p>How do people in this society relate to one another? What is the most important social unit? Is it the immediate family, a larger clan or tribe, a professional guild, or an individual''s loyalty to a city-state or nation? This helps us to determine a culture''s social hierarchy, where their loyalties lie, and their perceived sense of identity.</p></li><li><p>Why do the members of society behave in this way? What are their core beliefs or worldviews? What does this society value the most? Is it strength, knowledge, wealth, community, or tradition? These values are often expressed through a culture''s [[Religion]], mythology, and laws, which shape the society''s moral compass and ultimate goals.<br></p></li></ul><img class="editor-image rounded-lg" src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/34420152/pexels-photo-34420152.jpeg?auto=compress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;h=650&amp;w=940" data-align="left" style="float: left; margin: 0px 1.5rem 1rem 0px;"><h3>Survival</h3><p>To determine a culture''s relationship with its environment, we need to ask ourselves four main questions:<br></p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p>What is their main water source?</p></li><li><p>What do they eat?</p></li><li><p>Where do they live?</p></li><li><p>What do they build shelters with?<br></p></li></ul><h4>Water</h4><p>Water is the most essential resource of all and the true foundation of survival. A society''s source of fresh water is the first and most important constraint that shapes its culture. It determines where people can live and dictates their relationship with the land.<br></p><p>The type of water source available will also create fundamentally different societies:<br></p><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p><strong>Rivers and Lakes</strong>: Rivers and lakes are known for being natural centres for civilization that often lead to permanent settlements, agriculture, and trade routes.</p></li><li><p><strong>Oases and Wells:</strong> In arid lands, oases and wells are isolated points of life. Cultures that are built around them are often focused more on conservation efforts, defence of the resource itself, and have to travel long distances between water sources.</p></li><li><p><strong>Rainfall:</strong> Cultures that depend on rainfall, especially seasonal monsoons, tend to develop a deeper connection to the weather, the seasons, and the sky. Their calendars, religions, and daily lives are often governed by the wet and dry seasons.</p></li><li><p><strong>Ice and snowmelt:</strong> Ice and snowmelt can often be a source of water in colder regions, and life is tied to seasonal thawing. These cultures tend to become experts at melting ice for water and timing their movements with the availability of liquid water sources.<br></p></li></ul><h4>Food</h4><ul class="prose-ul"><li><p><strong>Farmers:</strong> Are they agriculturalists who cultivate crops? If so, they are tied to a specific piece of fertile land and their lives will be governed by the seasons of planting and harvesting.</p></li><li><p><strong>Hunter-Gatherers:</strong> Do they survive by hunting wild animals and foraging for plants? This lifestyle requires a deep knowledge of the local ecosystem and often involves seasonal migration to follow food sources.</p></li><li><p><strong>Pastoralists:</strong> Do they raise and follow herds of domesticated animals (like cattle, goats, or a fantasy equivalent)? Their lives are nomadic, centred around the needs of their animals for pasture and water.<br></p></li></ul><h4>Location</h4><p>Once we have determined a culture''s main food source, we can then determine their settlement pattern. Farmers will often build permanent towns and cities because they are bound by the land they sow. On the contrary, hunter-gatherers and pastoralists tend live in mobile camps with temporary or portable shelters.<br></p><h4>Shelter</h4><p>The local environment will also dictate a culture''s architecture. A society in a dense forest will build shelters with wood, while one in a rocky desert will use stone and clay. The available [[Natural Resources]] will also shape their tools, their technology, and their art.</p><p></p><h3>Organizations</h3><p>A culture''s survival strategy directly shapes its social structure by defining key concepts like property, leadership, and family size. The way a society gets its food and water is the foundation upon which its entire social pyramid is built.<br></p><h4>Farmer Organizations</h4><p>Because farmers are tied to a specific piece of land that they invest in for years, the concept of land ownership often becomes central to their society. This creates a social hierarchy where land ownership evolves into a natural division between those who own the land (nobles) and those who work it (peasants). Settled populations also require rulers, laws, soldiers, and tax collectors to manage and defend the land and its [[Natural Resources]]. Farming cultures also tend to have more children who can provide more hands to work in the fields, making extended families the cultural norm.<br></p><h4>Hunter-Gatherer Organizations</h4><p>Because hunter-gatherer cultures are constantly moving to follow food sources, owning land is a meaningless concept to them. Survival instead depends on cooperation and shared resources. With no accumulated wealth in the form of property or ownership, their social status is often a merit of skill rather than class. This tends to lead to a more equal social structure. Societies are also typically organized into small, flexible family groups that can travel easily. Sometimes a leader may be chosen for a specific task like hunting, but their leadership is typically fluid rather than having a permanent, absolute authority over the culture.<br></p><h4>Nomadic Herder Organizations</h4><p>Because a herder''s wealth is tied to their mobile herds and livestock, their social structure is built around protecting their culture''s movable property. Society is usually organized around large, extended family groups (clans/tribes) that collectively own and manage livestock herds. These clans will also band together into larger tribes for mutual defence. Leadership typically falls to the male heads of the most powerful families who control the largest herds. They also must constantly defend their herds from predators and rival tribes, which fosters a strong warrior culture.<br></p><h3>Core Beliefs</h3><p>A culture''s core beliefs are a direct reflection of what the culture needs to do to survive. Their gods, values, and myths are created to explain and sanctify the forces that have the most power over their lives.<br></p><h4>Farmer Beliefs</h4><p>A farmer''s life is typically governed by forces they can''t control but must understand: the sun, the rain, the earth, and the seasons. Their goal is to create order out of the chaos. They tend to worship deities of the sun, earth, and water. Their major religious festivals are also often tied to the cycles of planting and harvesting. They tend to value tradition, patience, and hard work. "Following the old ways" is important to their culture because it is proven to lead to a successful harvest, which is essential to their culture''s survival. Farmer cultures often see the world as a struggle between the order of their meticulously cultivated fields and the chaos of the untamed wilderness surrounding them.<br></p><h4>Hunter-Gatherer Beliefs</h4><p>A hunter-gatherer''s survival depends on a deep, respectful relationship with the natural world around them. They see themselves as a part of nature, rather than its masters. They typically practice a form of animism, which is a belief that all things like animals, plants, rivers, and even rocks have a spirit. To survive, they need to live in balance with these other spirits and show them respect. They tend to value community, generosity, and adaptability. Hoarding resources is typically a major taboo since the group''s survival depends on sharing. They often see time as cyclical since it follows the repeating patterns of seasons, animal migrations, and celestial events.<br></p><h4>Nomadic Herders</h4><p>A herder''s life is defined by movement, freedom, and the constant need to protect their herds under a vast, open sky. Their primary deities are often powerful sky gods who control the weather. They also practice ancestor worshipping, revering the spirits of past generations who guide them and their flocks. They typically value honour, loyalty, and hospitality. In a mobile society without formal laws, a person''s word and their loyalty to their clan is crucial. They see themselves as stewards of their animals and guardians of their clan''s lineage. The history of their culture becomes an oral epic of its greatest leaders and daring journeys.<br></p><h3>Combination Cultures</h3><p>Most historical cultures are a blend of these "pure" archetypes, adapting their survival strategies to the specific opportunities and limitations of their environment. These hybrid models often create more complex and resilient societies.<br></p><h4>Agro-Pastoralism</h4><p>This is the most common combination of farming and herding. A society''s primary food source is farming, but they also keep herds of domesticated animals. The animals provide manure to fertilize the fields, labour for pulling plows, and a secondary source of food in the form of milk and meat, and materials like wool and leather.<br></p><h4>Transhumance</h4><p>Seasonal herding and farming is a more specialized version of agro-pastoralism called transhumance. The bulk of the population lives in a permanent farming settlement, while a few designated herders move the livestock to different grazing lands with the seasons. In the summer, herders will take the flocks up into cool mountain pastures and in the winter, they bring them back down into warmer valleys. These cultures often emerge in mountainous regions.<br></p><h4>Foraging Farmers</h4><p>This type of culture occurs when a society cultivates some crops through farming, but still gets a significant portion of its food from the wild in terms of hunting and foraging. A village might have small, cultivated plots of land, but they supplement their diet by hunting in the surrounding forest, fishing in the local river, and gathering wild plants. These cultures tend to emerge in heavily forested or coastal areas where the abundance of natural resources and strategic geographic positioning foster unique patterns of settlement and social organization. The dense canopy of ancient woodlands provides not only shelter and building materials but also rich hunting grounds and a diverse array of edible plants, fungi, and medicinal herbs that shape both subsistence practices and spiritual beliefs. Similarly, coastal populations develop intricate knowledge systems around tidal patterns, seasonal fish migrations, and marine ecosystems, leading to sophisticated navigation techniques, boat-building traditions, and elaborate networks of trade that extend far beyond their immediate shores. The constant interaction with these environments—whether threading through towering trees along established forest paths or reading the subtle changes in ocean currents and weather patterns—becomes deeply embedded in the collective identity, oral traditions, and ceremonial practices of these societies.</p>', 'Learn about what world building is, how it works, and how to get started your own world building adventure!', 'World-Building', 16, 'Beginner', 4.6, 'Danielle Barker', '{worldbuilding,guide,"physical worldbuilding","culture worldbuilding"}', true, '2025-09-21 19:18:18.025013', '2025-10-25 20:42:17.425', NULL, NULL, 'dd4c49a5-f29b-4b83-b201-e4e54fdf25fa');


