[h5|ca3b7987-65fa-410a-8c63-eb6f5a3666ab]Adolescence (Ages 13–17)[/h5]
[ul]
- [b]The Lonely Vigil:[/b] Spending a night alone in the flats marks transition into “youth.” After this, education becomes specialized.
- [b]Apprenticeship:[/b] Teens shadow specific adults depending on aptitude:
-- Hunters join the Hornbearers.
-- Preservers learn with the Jar Mothers.
-- Traders join caravans.
-- Whisperers train in memory and song.
- [b]Cultural Training:[/b] Shadow-names and myths become more complex. Youth learn the proverbs, taboos, and Saltfolk codes in depth.
- [b]Storm Training:[/b] Adolescents are deliberately walked into mild storms with elders, to learn orientation and survival.
[/ul]
[p][/p]
[h5|c153e028-df19-4400-936a-0e371a878d89]The Hunt / Vessel Rites at 18[/h5]
[ul]
- These mark the completion of education:
-- [b]The Bighorn Rite:[/b] For scouts/hunters.
-- [b]Rite of the Vessel:[/b] For preservers/providers.
- Both confirm not just adulthood, but mastery of what has been taught.
[/ul]
[p][/p]
[h5|648c1977-d0fc-45f1-9e47-a3b3a2785001]Old World Knowledge[/h5]
[ul]
- [b]Fragments Only:[/b] Children hear about the Old World through scraps — a textbook page, a hymn, an elder’s memory.
- [b]Mythic Distance:[/b] Most “Old World” knowledge feels legendary, half-believed. Airplanes, oceans, and cities sound like folktales.
- [b]Pragmatic Filtering:[/b] Old knowledge that’s useful survives (solar panel repair, salt chemistry, medicine). The rest (like literature or abstract science) erodes into myth.
[/ul]
[p][/p]
[h5|93a5a843-9f0a-4b02-9455-b36cbd146b65]Religion & Education[/h5]
[ul]
- Religious instruction isn’t separate — it’s embedded. Every lesson has mythic framing:
-- Water rules are tied to the Salt Mother.
-- Greed lessons are tied to the Hollow Man.
-- Storm survival is tied to the Storm Children.
[/ul]
[p][/p]
[h5|4c83ef5d-6920-4c8d-b1e6-c23d34f97f5e]Teaching Methods[/h5]
[ul]
- [b]Oral:[/b] Chants, proverbs, stories.
- [b]Demonstration:[/b] Adults showing, children copying.
- [b]Trial:[/b] Children tested by circumstance — let loose to fail safely, so they learn.
- [b]Communal:[/b] Several families’ children often taught together at wells, during hunts, or at work.
[/ul]
[p][/p]
', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '33081217', '2025-10-07 13:55:13.70752', NULL, '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89', NULL, NULL);
