INSERT INTO public.ethnicities (id, name, origin, physical_traits, cultural_traits, traditions, language, religion, social_structure, history, geography, "values", customs, genre, user_id, created_at, article_content, notebook_id, image_url, image_caption) VALUES ('df033563-9468-4570-8f02-166d353c4276', 'Letharian', '', '', 'The current generations of Letharian have inherited dialects, traditions, relics, and living architecture from their ancestors and other Grove members. To be initiated into a Grove as a new member, the individual must form a Mossbond with the most Ancient surviving Letharian (typically in a semi-sessile state), and slice their palm to release the sap from their veins, and touch their palm to the roots of the Ancient Elder. This solidifies their Mossbond to the Grove itself, and the candidate is then initiated into the Deep Network where they can telepathically communicate with the Ancient Elder, as well as other Grove members. If the Mossbond is rejected by the Ancient Elder, the candidate is then exiled from the Grove and may not return until after the passing of the Ancient Elder, when a new Ancient Elder takes their place.





The Photosynthetic Communion that takes place each morning is considered a ceremonious ritual that is devoted to the Green Goddess as a form of honour, gratitude, and respect. It is a time of worship, silence, and devotion to the healing energies they can provide to the Earth. It is considered disrespectful to accidentally miss or refuse to attend Photosynthetic Communion.





When individuals inherit living architecture from their ancestors or other Grove members, it is considered sacred because it has been growing over time to suit the maker''s needs. Upon inheritance, the Letharian are meant to perform a sap-bonding ritual with the structure so that it can absorb their biological markers in order to personalize itself and begin growing more in line with their needs, instead of their predecessor''s. 





Their folklore and songs are fragmented pieces that are spread worldwide throughout the mycelial network. Each Grove is responsible for its own harmonies and chants, ritualizing singing them into existence so that they will not be forgotten from memory. It is said that when the Deep Network grow strong enough, Groves across the globe that are connected through the network will be able to sing each part of their song at the same time, piecing together a harmonizing frequency that would cure the Earth of its mutated Verdant growth.





There are efforts to conserve this knowledge, culture, rituals, and traditions among Ancient Letharian, but modern generations have begun adapting certain aspects of the culture as their ethnicity evolves over centuries, rather than shorter timespans like precursor humans.', '{"The Letharian calendar revolves around the community''s biological rhythms and ecological cycles rather than the historical commemorations of their precursor humans","which has developed into traditions that celebrate the crossroads of consciousness","seasonal changes","and community growth. The festivals and rituals they hold are multi-functional","offering spiritual observance","communal bonding","biological synchronization","and strengthening of network consciousness. These traditions reflect the Letharian understanding that individual wellbeing is dependent on balanced ecological and social harmonies.","The Great Seasonal Festivals","Awakening Tide (Spring Equinox)","The Awakening Tide is the most celebrated festival in the Letharian calendar because it marks the renewal of photosynthetic capacity and communal energy cycles after winter dormancy. The festival begins with the Dawn Communion","which is a three day period where local Groves gather together in carefully designed photosynthetic amphitheatres to experience a collective energy awakening as their biological systems resynchronize with the increasing solar intensities.","After the Dawn Communion","the Letharian hold the Symbiotic Renewal Ceremony","which forms the spiritual centrepiece of the Awakening Tide. The Grove community undergoes a ritual cleaning of their plant partnerships","renews symbiotic bonds","and dedicates themselves to ecological stewardship during the coming growing season. Sapling Stage Letharian are often given their first permanent plant partnerships during this ceremony","while established Grove members recommit to their existing biological relationships and communal responsibilities.","At the end of the Awakening Tide","a Network Harmonization ritual concludes the festival through an extended Grove-wide telepathic communion to re-establish social bonds","share collective goals for the growing season","and introduces new community members into the local mycelial network. Network Harmonization rituals can last for days as entire Groves experience shared consciousness at levels that are impossible during their daily lives.","Flowering Peak (Summer Solstice)","The Flowering Peak Festival celebrates maximum biological and social activity through the most elaborate communal gatherings in the Letharian calendar year. It emphasizes peak network connectivity","reproductive ceremonies","and community achievement celebrations to showcase the bounty of spring and early summer growth efforts.","It begins with the Great Network Meeting","which involves linking consciousness networks across Groves on unprecedented scales around the world to share experiences",knowledge,"and collective decision-making that affects the entire Letharian species. Major policy decisions","resource allocation agreements","and long-term planning between groves often take place during these extended network sessions. These sessions are led by Grove councils and witnesses by Grove community members.","During Flowering Peak","the Rootmate Bonding Celebrations also take place","with courtship culminations","partnership ceremonies","and reproductive rituals that receive community support through network enhancement during peak biological activity periods. The Flowering Peak festival''s atmosphere provides Grove members with the optimal conditions for successful symbiotic bonding and the integration of new partnerships within the community.","Near the end of the Flowering Peak festival","the Grove council holds a community achievement celebration at the Grove Thicket","where successful ecological restoration projects","artistic masterpieces","technological innovations","and knowledge achievements are shared with Grove members to celebrate their contributions to the community''s wellbeing. This reinforces Letharian community values while inspiring further growth and development.","Harvest Wisdom (Autumn Equinox)","The Harvest Wisdom festival focuses on knowledge preservation","community preparation for winter months","and gratitude for the growth that the Grove achieved during the active growing season. It emphasizes reflection","learning consolidation","and introspection to guide community development during the dormant season.","To preserve memories","a ceremony is held that involves encoding significant experiences from the growing season into permanent mycelial network storage","community art projects","and consciousness preservation systems to maintain important wisdom through the winter dormancy periods. The Ancient community members often share wisdom teachings during the ceremony. There is also a ritual of giving blessings and gratitude for food plants","mineral sources","and environmental resources that have supported the Grove community throughout the growing season. Grove members commit to winter resource sharing and conservation practices to sustain the community through the dormant period.","The Grove council provides opportunities to members for collective evaluation of community decisions","individual growth","and ecological relationships over the past year","with planning sessions for improvements and adaptations that may be needed for the next coming cycle. This is typically when community policy changes and role reassignments happen within the Grove.","Deep Rest (Winter Solstice)","The Deep Rest Festival is the most introspective and spiritually intensive through its emphasis of network communion","consciousness exploration","and connection to ancestral wisdom during a biologically dormant period where individual activity decreases to allow for a deepened collective awareness.","The festival is marked by the Great Network Dive","which involves an extended Grove-wide meditation that can last for weeks","with the entire community entering a deep network communion to allow access to the Letharian-wide consciousness","ancestral memories","and prophetic awareness. Throughout the Great Network Dive","individual identity temporarily dissolves into a collective experience during the deepest phase of the ceremony.","After the three-week-long ceremony concludes","a wisdom consultation provides Grove members with the opportunity to seek guidance from Ancient Elders","the preserved consciousness of deceased Grove members","and deeper levels of network awareness that are only accessible during the Deep Rest Festival. Once members have been given the information they need","they are able to use it to create a memory palace together","where they build an elaborate mental network to preserve the community''s knowledge","individual experiences","and cultural wisdom that is accessible to future generations. These consciousness constructions become permanent features of the Deep Network''s architecture.","Life Transition Celebrations","Sapling Recognition (Adolescence)","Sapling Recognition celebrates the transition from childhood biological dependence to independent symbiotic function while establishing adult community roles and network responsibilities. The ceremonies typically occur between ages 18-22 when biological integration has stabilized and individual capabilities have become apparent.","Network Competency Trials test the individual''s ability to maintain independent network communication","contribute to community decision-making","and handle the psychological demands of adult network connectivity without compromising individual identity or community harmony.","Specialization Ceremonies involve formal recognition of the individual''s emerging community role—whether as Cultivator",Guardian,"or Bridge-gendered specialist—with training assignments","mentorship arrangements","and community responsibility delegation that reflects their capabilities and community needs.","Daily and Seasonal Superstitions","Network Protection Beliefs","There are superstitions among Letharians that involve vulnerable connections where strong emotional states can permanently damage their network connectivity","and certain lunar phases can even make network communication dangerous. It is thought that unresolved conflicts can poison a Grove''s Deep Network channels. These beliefs have lead to Letharians having elaborate emotional regulation practices and conflict resolution protocols before participating in network communions. There are also fears about consciousness \"bleeding\" between individuals during deep network contact","where their personality might become absorbed by stronger network users","or their identity might be dissolved through excessive Deep Network participation. These fears have created complicated protocols for daily network interactions to preserve individual identities.","Seasonal Transition Superstitions","It is believed that fighting natural seasonal transitions can cause Letharians biological instability","to become disconnected to the Deep Network","and the Grove community will be exiled by ecological forces. As a result","these beliefs create a strong social pressure for seasonal behavioural compliance and a resistance to \"unseasonable\" activities or emotional states. It is also believed that there are lucky and unlucky times for major life decisions","partnership choices","and community role changes based on seasonal cycles","lunar phrase","and the state of the Deep Network. These beliefs heavily influence the timing of the major life events for Letharian communities","including community planning decisions.","Ecological Relationship Superstitions","It is also believed that a Letharian who mistreats their plant partner will cause Grove-wide ecological disasters that carry plant curses or blights from failed partnerships","and that plant souls can interfere with new symbiotic relationships. These have resulted in the Letharians having elaborate plant care rituals and official partnership dissolution ceremonies as they evolve through their extended lifetimes.","Many believe that wasteful consumption of resources can cause ecological retaliation","and hoarding resources will attract dangerous attention from Verdant-corrupted entities","or disrespecting mineral sources causes geological instability.","Community Cohesion Customs","Conflict Resolution Traditions","All community disputes need to be resolved through network meditation that is mediated by Bridge-gendered communication specialists who facilitate understanding between conflicting consciousness patterns to restore the harmony of the Deep Network. All unresolved conflicts are seen as a threat because they weaken Grove and attract external dangers. Through Forgiveness Ceremonies","Bridge-gendered mediators provide the opportunity for community members to address their grievances","seek reconciliation","and restore their damaged relationships in a ritualized apology process that involves the entire Grove''s participation and collective commitment through the Deep Network to repair the relationship.","Community Decision-Making Customs","All major decisions among Grove communities must be made through extended Deep Network consultation","which involves every Grove member joining in collective consciousness for a consultation and evaluation of proposed choices. Decisions that are made without proper network consultation are considered illegitimate and dangerous. The Grove Council then takes more serious matters into consultation with the Ancient Elders whose extended lifespans and deep network integration provide guidance for the long-term benefit of the Grove community","its planning","and species-wide decision-making. Major decisions that are made without consulting an Ancient Elder first are considered reckless and potentially catastrophic."}', 'The main form of language among Letharian are through spoken Elven-like dialects that evolve based on their Grove''s location, precursor human ethnicities, and the moss type of their partner species. However, communication across Mossbonds is telepathic and does not take the form of a dialect that would be detectable to precursor humans. This means that Rootmates who speak different dialects are still able to communicate with each other telepathically while they learn the other''s dialect, or create a dialect of their own. Grove dialects evolve over time, and individuals who are in the Ancient life stage are confined to only being able to communicate through the Deep Network telepathically. 





Mossbonds allow Rootmates and Grove members to communicate telepathically with each other through frequencies of mycelial networks that are engrained in the Deep Network. These are often described as melodies, harmonies, or whispers among the Letharian. 





To communicate with humans, a Letharian must be a Bridge-gendered individual who can transcend language barriers and has deep knowledge of human dialects for translation.', '', '', '', '', '{}', '{"The Letharian calendar revolves around the community''s biological rhythms and ecological cycles rather than the historical commemorations of their precursor humans","which has developed into traditions that celebrate the crossroads of consciousness","seasonal changes","and community growth. The festivals and rituals they hold are multi-functional","offering spiritual observance","communal bonding","biological synchronization","and strengthening of network consciousness. These traditions reflect the Letharian understanding that individual wellbeing is dependent on balanced ecological and social harmonies.","The Great Seasonal Festivals","Awakening Tide (Spring Equinox)","The Awakening Tide is the most celebrated festival in the Letharian calendar because it marks the renewal of photosynthetic capacity and communal energy cycles after winter dormancy. The festival begins with the Dawn Communion","which is a three day period where local Groves gather together in carefully designed photosynthetic amphitheatres to experience a collective energy awakening as their biological systems resynchronize with the increasing solar intensities.","After the Dawn Communion","the Letharian hold the Symbiotic Renewal Ceremony","which forms the spiritual centrepiece of the Awakening Tide. The Grove community undergoes a ritual cleaning of their plant partnerships","renews symbiotic bonds","and dedicates themselves to ecological stewardship during the coming growing season. Sapling Stage Letharian are often given their first permanent plant partnerships during this ceremony","while established Grove members recommit to their existing biological relationships and communal responsibilities.","At the end of the Awakening Tide","a Network Harmonization ritual concludes the festival through an extended Grove-wide telepathic communion to re-establish social bonds","share collective goals for the growing season","and introduces new community members into the local mycelial network. Network Harmonization rituals can last for days as entire Groves experience shared consciousness at levels that are impossible during their daily lives.","Flowering Peak (Summer Solstice)","The Flowering Peak Festival celebrates maximum biological and social activity through the most elaborate communal gatherings in the Letharian calendar year. It emphasizes peak network connectivity","reproductive ceremonies","and community achievement celebrations to showcase the bounty of spring and early summer growth efforts.","It begins with the Great Network Meeting","which involves linking consciousness networks across Groves on unprecedented scales around the world to share experiences",knowledge,"and collective decision-making that affects the entire Letharian species. Major policy decisions","resource allocation agreements","and long-term planning between groves often take place during these extended network sessions. These sessions are led by Grove councils and witnesses by Grove community members.","During Flowering Peak","the Rootmate Bonding Celebrations also take place","with courtship culminations","partnership ceremonies","and reproductive rituals that receive community support through network enhancement during peak biological activity periods. The Flowering Peak festival''s atmosphere provides Grove members with the optimal conditions for successful symbiotic bonding and the integration of new partnerships within the community.","Near the end of the Flowering Peak festival","the Grove council holds a community achievement celebration at the Grove Thicket","where successful ecological restoration projects","artistic masterpieces","technological innovations","and knowledge achievements are shared with Grove members to celebrate their contributions to the community''s wellbeing. This reinforces Letharian community values while inspiring further growth and development.","Harvest Wisdom (Autumn Equinox)","The Harvest Wisdom festival focuses on knowledge preservation","community preparation for winter months","and gratitude for the growth that the Grove achieved during the active growing season. It emphasizes reflection","learning consolidation","and introspection to guide community development during the dormant season.","To preserve memories","a ceremony is held that involves encoding significant experiences from the growing season into permanent mycelial network storage","community art projects","and consciousness preservation systems to maintain important wisdom through the winter dormancy periods. The Ancient community members often share wisdom teachings during the ceremony. There is also a ritual of giving blessings and gratitude for food plants","mineral sources","and environmental resources that have supported the Grove community throughout the growing season. Grove members commit to winter resource sharing and conservation practices to sustain the community through the dormant period.","The Grove council provides opportunities to members for collective evaluation of community decisions","individual growth","and ecological relationships over the past year","with planning sessions for improvements and adaptations that may be needed for the next coming cycle. This is typically when community policy changes and role reassignments happen within the Grove.","Deep Rest (Winter Solstice)","The Deep Rest Festival is the most introspective and spiritually intensive through its emphasis of network communion","consciousness exploration","and connection to ancestral wisdom during a biologically dormant period where individual activity decreases to allow for a deepened collective awareness.","The festival is marked by the Great Network Dive","which involves an extended Grove-wide meditation that can last for weeks","with the entire community entering a deep network communion to allow access to the Letharian-wide consciousness","ancestral memories","and prophetic awareness. Throughout the Great Network Dive","individual identity temporarily dissolves into a collective experience during the deepest phase of the ceremony.","After the three-week-long ceremony concludes","a wisdom consultation provides Grove members with the opportunity to seek guidance from Ancient Elders","the preserved consciousness of deceased Grove members","and deeper levels of network awareness that are only accessible during the Deep Rest Festival. Once members have been given the information they need","they are able to use it to create a memory palace together","where they build an elaborate mental network to preserve the community''s knowledge","individual experiences","and cultural wisdom that is accessible to future generations. These consciousness constructions become permanent features of the Deep Network''s architecture.","Life Transition Celebrations","Sapling Recognition (Adolescence)","Sapling Recognition celebrates the transition from childhood biological dependence to independent symbiotic function while establishing adult community roles and network responsibilities. The ceremonies typically occur between ages 18-22 when biological integration has stabilized and individual capabilities have become apparent.","Network Competency Trials test the individual''s ability to maintain independent network communication","contribute to community decision-making","and handle the psychological demands of adult network connectivity without compromising individual identity or community harmony.","Specialization Ceremonies involve formal recognition of the individual''s emerging community role—whether as Cultivator",Guardian,"or Bridge-gendered specialist—with training assignments","mentorship arrangements","and community responsibility delegation that reflects their capabilities and community needs.","Daily and Seasonal Superstitions","Network Protection Beliefs","There are superstitions among Letharians that involve vulnerable connections where strong emotional states can permanently damage their network connectivity","and certain lunar phases can even make network communication dangerous. It is thought that unresolved conflicts can poison a Grove''s Deep Network channels. These beliefs have lead to Letharians having elaborate emotional regulation practices and conflict resolution protocols before participating in network communions. There are also fears about consciousness \"bleeding\" between individuals during deep network contact","where their personality might become absorbed by stronger network users","or their identity might be dissolved through excessive Deep Network participation. These fears have created complicated protocols for daily network interactions to preserve individual identities.","Seasonal Transition Superstitions","It is believed that fighting natural seasonal transitions can cause Letharians biological instability","to become disconnected to the Deep Network","and the Grove community will be exiled by ecological forces. As a result","these beliefs create a strong social pressure for seasonal behavioural compliance and a resistance to \"unseasonable\" activities or emotional states. It is also believed that there are lucky and unlucky times for major life decisions","partnership choices","and community role changes based on seasonal cycles","lunar phrase","and the state of the Deep Network. These beliefs heavily influence the timing of the major life events for Letharian communities","including community planning decisions.","Ecological Relationship Superstitions","It is also believed that a Letharian who mistreats their plant partner will cause Grove-wide ecological disasters that carry plant curses or blights from failed partnerships","and that plant souls can interfere with new symbiotic relationships. These have resulted in the Letharians having elaborate plant care rituals and official partnership dissolution ceremonies as they evolve through their extended lifetimes.","Many believe that wasteful consumption of resources can cause ecological retaliation","and hoarding resources will attract dangerous attention from Verdant-corrupted entities","or disrespecting mineral sources causes geological instability.","Community Cohesion Customs","Conflict Resolution Traditions","All community disputes need to be resolved through network meditation that is mediated by Bridge-gendered communication specialists who facilitate understanding between conflicting consciousness patterns to restore the harmony of the Deep Network. All unresolved conflicts are seen as a threat because they weaken Grove and attract external dangers. Through Forgiveness Ceremonies","Bridge-gendered mediators provide the opportunity for community members to address their grievances","seek reconciliation","and restore their damaged relationships in a ritualized apology process that involves the entire Grove''s participation and collective commitment through the Deep Network to repair the relationship.","Community Decision-Making Customs","All major decisions among Grove communities must be made through extended Deep Network consultation","which involves every Grove member joining in collective consciousness for a consultation and evaluation of proposed choices. Decisions that are made without proper network consultation are considered illegitimate and dangerous. The Grove Council then takes more serious matters into consultation with the Ancient Elders whose extended lifespans and deep network integration provide guidance for the long-term benefit of the Grove community","its planning","and species-wide decision-making. Major decisions that are made without consulting an Ancient Elder first are considered reckless and potentially catastrophic."}', 'Fantasy', '33081217', '2025-10-07 16:58:57.296518', NULL, '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89', '', '');
INSERT INTO public.ethnicities (id, name, origin, physical_traits, cultural_traits, traditions, language, religion, social_structure, history, geography, "values", customs, genre, user_id, created_at, article_content, notebook_id, image_url, image_caption) VALUES ('0fdcf508-8ba9-4850-97f9-612815d7fb75', 'Reedweavers', '', '', 'The Reedweavers are the wetland dwellers who have embraced what some settlements fear most—symbiosis with the Verdancy. Where Saltfolk build walls of salt and Vaultmen walls of concrete against the Green Tide, the Reedweavers have learned to dance with it, cultivating beneficial plant partnerships in the vast marshes and bogs between former cities. They are a culture born of adaptation, patience, and the delicate art of distinguishing friend from foe in a world where every vine might mean salvation or destruction.





They live in elevated settlements woven from living reeds and salvaged materials, their homes rising from misty waterways on stilts of cultivated bamboo and reclaimed metal. Their skin carries the perpetual dampness of their environment—pale and often tinted faintly green from constant exposure to beneficial plant compounds, hands stained with the rich earth of their floating gardens. They move through their watery domain with the fluid grace of those born to wetlands, equally at home poling reed boats through narrow channels or wading knee-deep through marsh grass that parts before them like a living curtain.





The Reedweavers have mastered the art of botanical diplomacy, reading the chemical signals that plants use to communicate and responding with carefully cultivated pheromone gardens that speak the Verdancy''s own language. They tend vast networks of symbiotic species—the Bloomfrogs that serve as mobile ecosystems, the filtering rushes that clean their water and the Kelp Keepers. Their children grow up learning to distinguish between the gentle green that heals and the hungry green that devours, developing an almost supernatural sensitivity to the intentions of plant life.





Unlike the militant resistance of other survivor communities, the Reedweavers are humanity''s attempt at negotiated peace with the new world, and living proof that evolution may not always mean conquest, but the possibility of partnership.', '{}', '', '', '', '', '', '{}', '{}', 'Fantasy', '33081217', '2025-10-07 16:58:58.867369', NULL, '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89', '', '');
INSERT INTO public.ethnicities (id, name, origin, physical_traits, cultural_traits, traditions, language, religion, social_structure, history, geography, "values", customs, genre, user_id, created_at, article_content, notebook_id, image_url, image_caption) VALUES ('dc0cff58-6d87-4eca-a3bc-3ee35a1948c6', 'Rootbound', '', '', '', '{}', '', '', '', '', '', '{}', '{}', 'Fantasy', '33081217', '2025-10-07 16:58:58.967693', NULL, '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89', '', '');
INSERT INTO public.ethnicities (id, name, origin, physical_traits, cultural_traits, traditions, language, religion, social_structure, history, geography, "values", customs, genre, user_id, created_at, article_content, notebook_id, image_url, image_caption) VALUES ('9ffe4c3d-98ca-4d81-aa17-78716ef4a792', 'Saltfolk', '', '', 'Physical Relics



• Scrap Relics: Pieces of Old World tech — radios, solar panels, glass bottles, watches — patched and repurposed until they hardly resemble their original function. These items often carry symbolic weight even if they no longer work.
• Salt-etched Icons: Some families keep relics carved from salt blocks, etched with protective sigils. These may have started as trade markers or tools but became heirlooms.
• Old Maps & Books: Crumbling atlases, waterlogged textbooks, hymnals, or journals survive in fragments. They’re treated as half-mythical — words deciphered, reinterpreted, and woven into folklore.




Places:



• The Salt Wells: Central gathering points, seen as sacred because they sustain life.
• Collapsed Outposts: Old ruined shelters in the flats that serve as “ancestor houses” — reminders of earlier Saltfolk who endured storms.




Intangible Inheritance



• Folklore & Oral Histories: Myths of the First Saltfolk who fled Verdancy, tales of children surviving storms, parables of betrayal and endurance. These stories shape morality more than written law.
• Songs: Fragments of Old World songs linger, but reworked — hymns stripped to a few haunting lines, Portuguese lullabies that mothers still hum, ballads that become chants during labor. Song is memory made audible.




Myths:



• The Salt Mother — a figure who withholds water but gives salt, teaching that scarcity is sacred.
• The Hollow Man — cautionary tale of one who let Verdancy breach the flats, teaching vigilance and distrust of greed.
• The Storm Children — born in the heart of dust storms, said to have eyes like glass; mythologizes resilience.




Traditions:



• Water Rites: Pouring shared water in unions, marking death by spilling water into salt.
• Salt Circles: Protective boundaries traced at births, unions, and funerals.
• Shadow-names: Secret names passed through families, meant to guard one’s spirit.
• The Great Glass Piles: Mounds of scavenged glass near Espera, glittering in the sun, treated almost like shrines to resilience.




Importance to Modern Generations



• Deeply Important: These inheritances are not luxuries — they are survival’s memory. To abandon them feels like cutting ties with what kept Espera alive.
• But Selective: Not all relics or traditions are equally preserved. Youth may see certain myths as superstition. Some elders cling fiercely, others adapt.
• Living Culture: Myths and relics are constantly reinterpreted — songs evolve, traditions shift. Preservation is not about static repetition but about using the past to make sense of now.




Efforts to Conserve vs. Erase



• Conservation:
-• Elders and storytellers guard folklore like treasure.
-• Healers preserve old remedies, often mixed with Rootbound knowledge despite prejudice.
-• Families pass relics to children, often with ceremony.
• Erasure / Resistance:
-• Some Saltfolk reject parts of the past that bring shame — names tied to betrayal, myths tied to fear of Hollowed.
-• There are efforts to suppress certain languages (e.g., younger folk dropping Portuguese/Spanish in favor of blunt Salt Cant).
-• Some wish to abandon relics they see as useless “Old World junk,” preferring new, pragmatic survival tools.', '{"The Saltfolk would have built traditions around the rhythm of survival: water",salt,storms,death,"and the rare moments of abundance. Every custom","whether sacred or playful","grows from these constants. The Saltfolk’s traditions revolve around scarcity transformed into ritual — rain",salt,storms,"sheep hunts",unions,"and deaths. Their festivals are brief but potent","moments of collective endurance turned into joy or solemnity. Superstitions thread daily life","keeping survival infused with meaning","Everyday Rituals & Customs","• Salt Circles: Drawn around cradles",sickbeds,"or doorways to ward against Verdancy. Breaking a salt circle is a grave taboo.","• Water Etiquette: Pouring out a few drops before drinking — an offering to the desert.","• Morning Dew-Rite: Children collect dew from tarps at dawn. Before drinking","they tap the gourd twice in thanks — a superstition that the desert “keeps giving.”","• Shadow-Names: A second","secret name whispered only to lovers or kin. Sharing it is an act of trust.","• Salt-Palm Apologies: Offering a pinch of salt in an open hand to make peace.","Major Traditions & Festivals","The First Rains (Feast of the Wells)","• Celebrated the first time each year when rainwater fills the cisterns.","• Everyone gathers at the central well; elders bless the water with salt.","• A communal feast follows — usually dried stores reconstituted into a large stew","sometimes sweetened with prickly pear syrup if available.","• Children run barefoot through the salt mud — a rare indulgence.","The Ram Feast (Bighorn Hunt)","• Happens whenever a hunting party returns with a sheep.","• The whole community eats together; hunters retell the dangers of the trek.","• Children receive the first bites of liver and marrow for strength.","• Horns are displayed in communal halls; sometimes carved into ceremonial horns blown at unions","council meetings","births or deaths/funerals.","Day of Silence (Storm Remembrance)","• Once a year","the Saltfolk honour those lost to storms.","• All speech ceases from dawn until the first stars. People communicate only with hand signs and gestures.","• At dusk","names of the dead are carved into salt blocks","then left to erode in the wind — symbolizing return to the desert.","The Union Rite (Water Binding)","• Romantic unions are marked by pouring water into a shared vessel and drinking together inside a salt circle.","• A communal feast follows","where families contribute small portions from their personal stores as a gesture and offering of prosperity and abundance.","• A superstition: if the water vessel cracks during the rite","the union will not endure.","The Salt Harvest Festival","• When a new vein of salt is mined or the flats yield a good season","Saltfolk celebrate by lining the settlement’s paths with glowing salt-crystal lanterns.","• Songs are sung — chants in English",Spanish,"or Portuguese fragments.","• Children are allowed to carve small salt figurines","which are then dissolved in water the next morning — teaching the impermanence of abundance in the desert.","Superstitions & Beliefs","• Never Waste a Drop: Spilling water on purpose brings misfortune; accidental spills require scattering salt to “balance the loss.”","• Stormborn Children: Babies born during a dust storm are thought to have “storm-sight” — an uncanny awareness or foresight.","• Hollow Eyes: If someone’s eyes go pale or “glasslike","” people whisper they are being claimed by the Verdancy. Protective salt smearing is performed.","• Salt Dreams: Some Saltfolk believe dreams of the sea are omens of death — because water in abundance belongs only to the dead.","• Numbers: Threes are lucky (trinity of salt",water,endurance),"while sevens are avoided — thought to represent the “creeping hunger” of the Verdancy.","Other Specific Customs","• Birth: Newborns are anointed with a smear of brine across the forehead","“marking them as children of scarcity.”","• Death: The dead are salted before burial or left to desiccate naturally in salt caverns. A ritual spill of water accompanies funerals.","• Coming of Age: At age thirteen","a youth must survive a night alone in the salt flats with only a gourd of water and a salt pouch. Returning marks entry into adulthood.","• Trade Days: When caravans arrive","stalls spring up with roasted insects","prickly pear skewers","and embroidered cloth patches. These days are half-market",half-festival,"often accompanied by music and storytelling."}', 'The Saltfolk’s speech is a layered survival dialect, shaped by Espera’s history as a refugee settlement, its geography near the southern border, and the constant drift of traders and migrants. Language here is not just communication — it’s a survival tool and a cultural anchor.





Core Language: Broken English (Salt Cant)



• English is the backbone, but it’s worn down: clipped, pragmatic, stripped of unnecessary flourishes. This “Salt Cant” favors short syllables and practical terms that can be shouted over wind and sand.
• Trade-born slang fills gaps. Saltfolk speech is littered with words from barter culture (Old World tech, medicinal jargon, Rootbound curses, etc.).
• Harsh desert life favours metaphors from salt, storms, hunger, and thirst. Example: “He’s brined” (meaning toughened), “her eyes stormed” (meaning angry).




Refugee Influence


Spanish and Portuguese words filter into the Saltfolk dialect, especially given Espera’s location in the U.S. Southwest and the collapse of São Paulo early in the Verdancy timeline. Refugees carried fragments of their tongues into Espera.



• Spanish influence: water terms (agua, pozo, sal, viento), family (madre, abuela), exclamations (¡Dios!, carajo), curses.
• Portuguese influence: survival words (fome – hunger, sede – thirst, saudade – longing for what’s gone), affectionate diminutives (-inho, -inha).
• Some refugee surnames survive intact, others blend into Espera’s naming system (e.g., Silva → Sil, Duarte → Duar, Santos → Sant).

These influences vary by quarter of Espera — areas where specific refugee groups settled. One alley might be heavy with Spanish borrowings, another with Portuguese cadences, another with clipped English salted with slang.





Regional Variations



• Central Espera (the salt flats core): Most stripped-down “Salt Cant,” minimal words, direct and harsh.
• Refugee Quarters: More loanwords from Spanish and Portuguese survive here. Songs, prayers, and family talk often use these tongues more fully, especially among older generations.
• Caravan Speech: Traders blend Salt Cant with fragments of other dialects from the wastes. They often act as linguistic bridges, spreading slang across settlements.




Ritual & Secret Languages



• Whispered Prayers: Some Saltfolk still whisper prayers in Spanish or Portuguese, even if they don’t fully understand the words. These carry a weight of longing and continuity.
• Shadow-names: Sometimes preserved in Old World tongues — a secret name in Portuguese might signal intimacy, even if daily speech is in Salt Cant.




Cultural Attitudes



• Saltfolk value clarity and brevity. Someone speaking too flowery, too long-winded, is distrusted. Language must cut like salt — short, sharp, stinging.
• But at the same time, there’s a deep reverence for song and story. Around fires, older tongues are brought out in full — Portuguese lullabies, Spanish ballads, fragments of English hymns. Language becomes a way to remember what was lost.', '', '', '', '', '{}', '{"The Saltfolk would have built traditions around the rhythm of survival: water",salt,storms,death,"and the rare moments of abundance. Every custom","whether sacred or playful","grows from these constants. The Saltfolk’s traditions revolve around scarcity transformed into ritual — rain",salt,storms,"sheep hunts",unions,"and deaths. Their festivals are brief but potent","moments of collective endurance turned into joy or solemnity. Superstitions thread daily life","keeping survival infused with meaning","Everyday Rituals & Customs","• Salt Circles: Drawn around cradles",sickbeds,"or doorways to ward against Verdancy. Breaking a salt circle is a grave taboo.","• Water Etiquette: Pouring out a few drops before drinking — an offering to the desert.","• Morning Dew-Rite: Children collect dew from tarps at dawn. Before drinking","they tap the gourd twice in thanks — a superstition that the desert “keeps giving.”","• Shadow-Names: A second","secret name whispered only to lovers or kin. Sharing it is an act of trust.","• Salt-Palm Apologies: Offering a pinch of salt in an open hand to make peace.","Major Traditions & Festivals","The First Rains (Feast of the Wells)","• Celebrated the first time each year when rainwater fills the cisterns.","• Everyone gathers at the central well; elders bless the water with salt.","• A communal feast follows — usually dried stores reconstituted into a large stew","sometimes sweetened with prickly pear syrup if available.","• Children run barefoot through the salt mud — a rare indulgence.","The Ram Feast (Bighorn Hunt)","• Happens whenever a hunting party returns with a sheep.","• The whole community eats together; hunters retell the dangers of the trek.","• Children receive the fi