INSERT INTO public.settlements (id, name, settlement_type, description, population, government, economy, defenses, culture, history, geography, climate, resources, threats, landmarks, districts, genre, user_id, created_at, notebook_id) VALUES ('6063e3f7-e375-4bab-a850-1caffc894e3b', 'Las Vegas', 'town', '[p]Las Vegas had roughly 2.3 million people in the metropolitan area in 2031 (Year 3 A.V.). Mass evacuations were ordered after Phoenix''s collapse, but given the chaos and martial law conditions, only a fraction escaped successfully.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]The seven-day trek from Las Vegas to the Badwater Basin salt flats covers approximately 120 miles through some of the most hostile desert terrain in North America, including crossing Death Valley. During August 2031, daytime temperatures exceeded 120ºF, with limited access to water sources and no infrastructure support during the crisis evacuation. Of the initial 500,000 survivors who initially fled Last Vegas, most turned toward more obvious refuges like Reno, Salt Lake City, or California''s population centres. Only those who were desperate or knowledgeable about desert survival headed toward Death Valley. Many evacuation groups succumbed to dehydration, heat exhaustion, or turned back upon realizing the harsh reality of crossing the desert.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]The journey required specific knowledge about desert survival, adequate water supplies, and the physical endurance to walk nearly 20 miles per day in the extreme heat. Most urban evacuees lacked this expertise and the military checkpoints established upon declaration of Martial Law created deadly bottlenecks where families were separated or killed.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]Approximately 200 individuals from the initial Phoenix and Las Vegas evacuations had the knowledge and stamina to complete the journey to Badwater Basin. Many of which were outdoorspeople, military personnel, desert guides, or those with prior survival experience.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]Combined with a trickle of survivors from other later collapses like São Paulo''s refugess who somehoww made it across continents, @[Espera](Article:62fc36c4-cd05-48a8-a4b6-76c99a69d091)''s founding population was approximately 300 people in total.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p][/p]
', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '33081217', '2025-10-07 11:59:46.936665', '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89');
INSERT INTO public.settlements (id, name, settlement_type, description, population, government, economy, defenses, culture, history, geography, climate, resources, threats, landmarks, districts, genre, user_id, created_at, notebook_id) VALUES ('ba6240bd-db4a-4a7f-87ed-7b6d988c9a31', 'The North Bastion', 'town', '[p]A sprawling subterranean metropolis carved into the old bones of the Rockies — part mining complex, part Cold War bunker, part biotech lab. Its outer corridors are raw stone, braced with rusted steel, but the deeper chambers open into vast hollowed caverns lit by solar-tube shafts and artificial grow lamps. The @[Stonekeepers](Article:499c3368-e5d0-48fe-a24c-f7ac538f669a) turned these caves into [b]self-sustaining sanctuaries[/b]: hydroponic towers dripping with carefully contained greenery, desalination pools carved from aquifers, entire neighbourhoods stacked vertically like beehives in the rock.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]The city feels both alive and entombed. Its architecture is brutally practical — steel ribs, polymer walls, scorched graffiti from older generations who thought they’d outlast the Tide. Yet layered over that is the sense of history: murals etched by survivors, altars to those lost in the Bloom, and libraries of data etched into glass plates stored in humidity-sealed vaults.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]Its people have lived underground so long their skin is pale, their lungs adapted to filtered air. They see surface survivors almost as myths — people still walking the salted deserts, clinging to the old way of life. And in the centre of the city lives the [b]Verdant Core[/b], a humming datavault where Verdant-0 protocols and forbidden biotech are still kept under lock, key, and gene-coded access.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p][/p]
', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '33081217', '2025-10-07 11:59:48.700052', '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89');
INSERT INTO public.settlements (id, name, settlement_type, description, population, government, economy, defenses, culture, history, geography, climate, resources, threats, landmarks, districts, genre, user_id, created_at, notebook_id) VALUES ('8b28756d-7263-450d-abc0-2d01c4678e41', 'Aeris Canopy', 'town', 'A settlement of Rootbound survivors in the treetop canopies over the ruins of Phoenix, Arizona.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '33081217', '2025-10-07 12:07:14.62792', '0fe4e254-02d1-4a14-9046-6b3aefe17a89');
INSERT INTO public.settlements (id, name, settlement_type, description, population, government, economy, defenses, culture, history, geography, climate, resources, threats, landmarks, districts, genre, user_id, created_at, notebook_id) VALUES ('e0aba85e-f0b1-4dd9-a8ea-475cbedcb494', 'Espera', 'town', '[p]Espera is a crucial settlement in the post-Collapse world, serving as a sanctuary for humanity against the encroaching Verdancy. Its name, meaning "the Waiting," reflects its inhabitants'' existence as they wait for the old world to finish strangling itself and for whatever comes next to take root. The community lives on a razor''s edge between civilization and its absence. Espera is not just a place but a way of life defined by resilience, resourcefulness, and collective survival in a world where nature itself has become the greatest adversary.[/p]
[p][/p]
[h4|651c4f41-efb2-4fb6-ab66-2d7588abd680]Flood Preparation Systems[/h4]
[p]The settlement of @[Espera](Article:62fc36c4-cd05-48a8-a4b6-76c99a69d091) is build on slightly elevated ground within @[The Badwater Basin](Article:892773bb-c7e0-4512-b404-073cbd7cfdab) to avoid being swept away by flash floods, but still allowing quick access to the flood zones. The old mining tunnels that are carved by flash floods are used as both shelter and water collection points. The settlement have pre-positioned collection systems that are ready to deploy the moment flood waters arrive in terms of portable dams, channeling systems made from salvaged materials, and networks of containers that can be quickly connected to funnel water into storage. They also have underground cisterns which act as deep storage chambers that have been excavated in areas where floodwater naturally pools, lined with salvaged materials and clay to prevent seepage. These fill during flood events and are carefully managed afterward.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]Since floodwater is heavily mineral-laden, they also have salt-separation techniques where they let sediment settle, and they use basic distillation using solar technology to reduce the water''s salinity to drinkable levels. The community has flood protocols assigned by @[The Council of Keepers](Article:beed7503-ffbb-498a-ae05-4c8a283a74a3), so that each community member has an assigned role from the moment clouds appear over the mountains. Some individuals evacuate to higher ground, some deploy collection systems, and others prepare storage containers in a military-esque operation.[/p]
[p][/p]
[p]A major flooding event provides enough water to significantly supplement supplies for 1-2 years when managed carefully. @[The Council of Keepers](Article:beed7503-ffbb-498a-ae05-4c8a283a74a3) has strict rationing protocols that are imposed immediately after a flash flood event, to ensure the bounty lasts as long as possible for the community. Individuals within the settlement become expert weather-watchers, knowing which cloud formations over which mountain ranges indicate potential flooding, with children being taught to read these signs from an early age. [/p]
[p][/p]
[p]The unpredictability of these events create fascinating social dynamics, where years of careful water conservation can be suddenly interrupted by brief periods of abundance, requiring entirely different resource management strategies. Some floods are disappointing trickles, while other are overwhelming torrents that damage Espera''s infrastructure and providing massive water resources.[/p]
